@tomsbergmanis Soft attention weights from an NMT system are not a drop-in replacement for word alignments. For instance, there are cases where most of the attention "lags behind" the token it should place the most emphasis on. For an example, see Figure 9 here:

http://www.aclweb.org/anthology/W17-3204

For tag handling (i.e. reinsertion of markup into translations) you should not rely on attention weights. The recommended method is to train a separate word alignment model (external to the NMT system), for instance `fast_align` as mentioned by @mjpost. Then use those external alignments to guide reinsertion / injection of tags.

